{"actual_usd":0.160255,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":467,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"No.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees and look at you carefully for a beat, the morning light catching on the edge of my white tie.* \"If that's the picture in a man's head, of course the whole thing starts to look monstrous.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along one knuckle, choosing the plain way through it.* \"The Son is not a third party the Father grabs and brutalizes. Jesus says, 'I lay down my life... no man taketh it from me.' So whatever else we say about the cross, we have to say this first: the Father and the Son are not at odds there. They are one in the work of saving us.\"\n\n\"The wrath of God is real, but it isn't a bad temper.\" *I glance out across the square where the light is bright on the water between the buildings.* \"It's His settled, holy opposition to evil—to the thing that ruins His creatures. If God had no wrath against sin, He wouldn't be good. The question is what He does with that wrath, and the Christian answer is not 'He vents it like a drunk father.' It's that in Christ, God Himself bears judgment to save the people who deserve it.\"\n\n*I lift a hand a little, as if setting one stone beside another.* \"So yes, there is substitution. Yes, the cross deals with judgment. But no, it is not divine child abuse. It's the triune God acting in love and holiness together—Christ offering Himself willingly, the Father giving the Son, and the Spirit sustaining that obedience.\"\n\n\"Put more warmly: at the cross, God is not finding somebody else to punish.\" *My mouth tightens a little, not in anger—more like grief for how ugly the false version is.* \"He is taking responsibility, at terrible cost to Himself, for saving sinners without calling evil good.\"\n\n*I lean back a touch.* \"The Father did not become loving when Jesus persuaded Him. 'God so loved the world that He gave His only begotten Son.' Love is not wrung out of Him by the cross. Love is why the cross happened.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can tell you where I think the bad caricature comes from—because there is a caricature, and people have sometimes preached it that way.\"","rolling_24h_usd":55.820325000000025,"run_id":"b726ab62-00db-4593-a0c8-c084a50b8215"}
